      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I've run into a nasty issue. The system has about 512KB of RAM, and over a 4-hour continuous run, we're seeing a steady leak of about 12KB. It's not crashing immediately, but it eventually hits the limit and triggers a hard fault. \n\nHere is a simplified version of the telemetry loop where I suspect the issue is:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data() {\n    while(system_running) {\n        SensorData* data = new SensorData();\n        data->timestamp = get_timestamp();\n        data->reading = read_adc();\n        \n        if (data->reading > THRESHOLD) {\n            log_event(data);\n        }\n        // I thought I was handling cleanup here, but the heap keeps climbing\n        // delete data; // commented out for testing\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `log_event` function copies the data to a buffer, but I can't tell if the leak is in the allocation itself or if `log_event` is holding onto something. What's the best systematic way to track this down on a bare-metal system without a full Valgrind setup?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
